If you could forward me those responses I could possibly find out what is going wrong.

Being dateless on Saturday, well not entirely true (but considering I had a bachlorette party to attend later that night, it was better to not bring a date), I dragged Ada with me to see 'Death Cab for Cutie'.      Despite some minor hiccups and whatnots that evening - our usual half hour of lateness because Ada was still figuring out an outfit while I sat in her driveway;  having to pay $20 for a lot near the Warfield, so we would avoid walking amongst the bums for too long;  seeing most of 'Pretty Girls Make Graves' from the side of the bar because we needed to get drinks first;  discovering the Warfield only offered cheap vodka and no Red Bull, which forced us to down some horrendous shots;  paying $3 in service fees to pull out $40 because we forgot to go to the bank beforehand;  finding the only open area in the pit had to be behind some 6' tall guy, who stood in front of us the entire time;  and the heat, the heat was so bad that we eventually had to move to the back of the room to finish watching - the show itself, turned out to be quite amazing.      As the last chords were played, Ada turned to me with a disturbed look. "Yea, that was a good concert and all. Um, did you happen to notice all the lesbians couples here tonight?? The two butch girls behind us in the pit kept rubbing their giant boobs against our backs."      "Um, actually no. I think they were just rubbing your back."      "Oh." With that, I leave you with one of my favorites. Title and Registration - Death Cab For Cutie The glove compartment isn't accurately named And everybody knows it. So i'm proposing a swift orderly change. Cause behind its door there's nothing to keep my fingers warm And all i find are souvenirs from better times Before the gleam of your taillights fading east To find yourself a better life. I was searching for some legal document As the rain beat down on the hood When i stumbled upon pictures i tried to forget And that's how this idea was drilled into my head Cause it's too important To stay the way it's been There's no blame for how our love did slowly fade And now that it's gone it's like it wasn't there at all And here i rest where disappointment and regret collide Lying awake at night There's no blame for how our love did slowly fade And now that it's gone it's like it wasn't there at all And here i rest where disappointment and regret collide Lying awake at night (up all night) When i'm lying awake at night.
And then, there were the happy times.
"Stop the madness," Ann says. I completely disagree. Enjoy: http://www.bikerfox.com/glamourshots/

Roller skating was a favorite amongst the kids at my elementary school.  I'd like to brag that I embraced it as whole-heartedly as the rest of them, but that would just be one FAT lie.  My first two trips to Skate City (located at none other than our local strip mall) found me panic-stricken and clinging to the rails in desperation.  'Twas a very lovely sight indeed. 

Lucky for me, all the kids held their birthdays at the rink.  So I had plenty of chances to return to that hell hole.  The next two visits found me off the stupid railing and plastered instead to the newly waxed and much too slippery floors.  I don't know when it happened but eventually I made it around that entire rink.  My mom was ecstatic.  In actuality, I think she was just relieved that her daughter wasn't a complete retard.  I mean, it did take four fucking trips before I learned how to balance.  By some odd twist of fate (or maybe just sheer determination to not fall ever again), I became quite the little skating queen that year.  Tricks, turns and yes, I even skated backwards.   Be jealous, I know. 

So imagine my excitement this past weekend, when I bought new skates for my halloween costume.  The salesperson assured me, "It's just like picking up a bicycle again. you never really forget how to". 

She did however, fail to mention that my skates are now 30 pounds heavier than when I was seven.  Fuck'n ay.  She also failed to remind me about the critical key to balancing on skates - using those damn front stoppers.

Looking back, I probably shouldn't have chosen Berkeley marina with its crappy uneven pavement as my practice arena.  It was my fault really.  Within ten feet of gliding away from the car, I tripped over a huge crack and fell backwards on my ass.  I had to dig the palm of my hands into the rocky asphalt to break the fall.  No, I didn't cry... even when the teenage kids in the parked car next to me burst out laughing.  Punks.

It took forty-five minutes of stumbling around before I re-mastered the pivot half turn. You remember that move right?  Haha, um ...well maybe not.  I went home with five blisters, two cuts and a fat ass bruise on my hand. I guess I won't be drinking and skating on halloween. 

"Don't drink and skate!!" - I should make stickers to pass out.

Birthplace? Saigon, Vietnam. The next place you want to visit? Italy. The worst thing about you? I can be a bitch. The best thing about being your friend? I will bake you brownies. Is honesty the best policy? Most of the time. Most humiliating moment? I have several. We should compare notes one of these days. What color is your underwear today? Pink. What's in the trunk of your car? volleyball, cds, flashlight, motor oil, tar remover (eh, so i'm anal too) and flip-flops What would your stripper name be (if given the opportunity)? Um, where did this come from? I don't know. Miss jackson? Though Ann would say: Taylor. Your bedroom is? Calm. First thing you think about when you wake up in the morning? Eggs or eggs today? Do you sleep with stuffed animals? Um, no. do you? What do you wear to bed? Undies. What personal items would you save in a fire? Photo albums and a ring my grandmother gave to me. Song you love but are embarrased to admit to? My heart will go on - Celine Dion (Yes, yes...keep the comments to yourself). How old were you when you had your first kiss? 11 Was there tongue involved? Only his. Your worst job ever? I was a hostess at Bullwinkle's in high school. We had to wear ranger outfits.. hats and all. What are your pet peeves? Slow drivers. Bad hygiene. Flakiness. Bad grammar except when used in slang expressions. And many, many more... The last time you received a real letter? In june, when Russ went to europe. What is the worst feeling in the world? Boredom. Do you live in the moment? Only when asked to.

We really need a president who can speak to the american public without sounding like a bumbling idiot. Bush was defensive (probably due to the fact that he was floundering on the questions) and at times seemingly exasperated with kerry in last night's debate. He is a fucking retard without the help of teleprompters and note cards from his white house assistants. "Someone tell me, who the hell is running this country?" If I had to hear him say one more time, "You know my opinion on _______. I can't say it any more plainly", without stumbling through the facts and repeating his 'political jargon' (most of which I've heard in past speeches), I was seriously going to hurl the remote at the tv.

Sigh, I loved clinton. Yes, even with the whole cigar fiasco. Who gives a fuck about that? He brought the federal budget into surplus after inheriting a deficit from his predecessor, curtailed federal spending, reduced the capital gains tax, signed welfare reform into law and a number of other initiatives that I don't remember or have time to look up right now.

--- from the transcript ----

MR. KERRY: Bush also promised America that he would go to war as a last resort. Those words mean something to me, as somebody who's been in combat: last resort. You've got to be able to look in the eyes of families and say to those parents, "I tried to do everything in my power to prevent the loss of your son and daughter.'' I don't believe the United States did that. And we pushed our allies aside. And so today we are 90 percent of the casualties and 90 percent costs - $200 billion, $200 billion that could have been used for health care, for schools, for construction, for prescription drugs for seniors.

And it's in Iraq. And Iraq is not even the center of the focus on the war on terror. The center is Afghanistan where, incidentally, there were more Americans killed last year than the year before, where the opium production is 75 percent of the world's opium production, where 40 to 60 percent of the economy of Afghanistan is based on opium, where the elections have been postponed three times. The president moved the troops there, he's got 10 times the number of troops in Iraq than he has in Afghanistan where Osama bin Laden is. Does that mean that Saddam Hussein was 10 times more important than Osama bin - than, excuse me - Saddam Hussein more important than Osama bin Laden? I don't think so.

............

Mr. Lehrer New question, Mr. President. Two minutes. Has the war in Iraq been worth the cost in American lives: 1,052 as of today?

............

MR. BUSH: Every life is precious. Every life matters. You know my hardest, the hardest part of the job is to know that I committed the troops in harm's way and then do the best I can to provide comfort for the loves ones who lost a son or a daughter or husband and wife.

And, you know, I think about Missy Johnson, fantastic young lady I met in Charlotte, N.C., she and her son, Brian. They came to see me. Her husband, P.J., got killed-been in Afghanistan, went to Iraq. You know, it's hard work to try to love her as best as I can knowing full well that the decision I made caused her, her loved one to be in harm's way.

I told her, after we prayed and teared up and laughed some, that I thought her husband's sacrifice was noble and worthy. Because I understand the stakes of this war on terror. I understand that we must find Al Qaeda wherever they hide, we must deal with threats before they fully materialize, and Saddam Hussein was a threat, and that we must spread liberty because in the long run the way to defeat hatred and tyranny and oppression is to spread freedom.

Missy understood that. That's what she told me her husband understood. So you say was it worth it? It wasn't-it's-every life is precious. That's what distinguishes us from the enemy. Everybody matters.

But I think it's worth it, Jim. I think it's worth it because I think, I know in the long term a free Iraq, a free Afghanistan will set such a powerful example in a part of the world that's desperate for freedom. It will help change the world. That we can look back and say we did our duty.

--- end of transcript ----

Um what did he say? When did it become our duty to change the world at the price of our children?  If you don't agree with me, I really don't care.  We live in a biased world, so fuck off. Oh, remember to vote please.  ;)

I was surfing, looking for something to distract me long enough so I could finish dessert. Dr. phil, reruns of Road Rules, VH1's 'The It Girls'. 'Shit, must everything suck all at once?? Even on cable?' Hmm...: 'Extreme makeover: The Home Edition - A show that builds hope, love and renewed vigor'. Renewed vigor? Eh, that's a first for reality TV. Have you seen this? They locate 'outstanding' (I'm using that term loosely since I don't know what's required for getting onto the show) families who are underprivileged and rebuild their home with help from sponsors and neighbors. What caught my eye was not the fact that I had found yet another reality show. Shocking really. But I was actually fascinated at how eight kids (yes, eight) could live in such a small house without killing one another. The scene then shifted to the dad: Stepping into the master bedroom for the first time and seeing a painting of his deceased wife hanging on the far wall. And there, for all us poor saps to enjoy... He walks over to the painting and starts kissing it and crying softly. 'I loved her so much. I wish she could see our new home now. All I ever wanted was to find and love her. Love her forever.' (yada yada yada...) Then all the kids poured into the bedroom and they too began crying at the sight of the painting. It was a mess. Such crap, I cried a river right into my ice cream. So much for dessert. Fuck'n reality shows.
